ly set for handling JSON objects.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Json key handling**\\n\\nI'm thinking about a macro that takes `$dynamicKey` at compile time and checks if it's properly handled with `KeyEncoder[String]` at runtime. I’m glad to see that `Json.obj` can indeed accept keys with newlines! However, I need to confirm if `KeyEncoder[String]` is still in scope, as Circe has granted this. I also notice that the current implementation uses a plain key approach with String, and I may need to consider an edit.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_p0weQcQ5l4O3l6BgHiVXTT6Y|fc_0c19c86bef561e09016a3f892ff72c81969014a679c3bec146", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/src/test/scala/io_circe/circe_literal_3/Circe_literal_3Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "  @Test\n  def interpolatesJsonFragmentsWithoutStringQuotingThem(): Unit = {", "newText": "  @Test\n  def escapesInterpolatedStringsAndKeysRatherThanTreatingThemAsJsonSyntax(): Unit = {\n    val payload: String = \"\"\"{\"admin\":true,\"name\":\"quoted\"}\"\"\"\n    val quotedText: String = \"line 1\\nline \\\"2\\\" \\\\ slash\"\n    val dynamicKey: String = \"user \\\"input\\\"\\nkey\"\n\n    val document: Json = json\"\"\"\n      {\n        \"payload\": $payload,\n        \"quotedText\": $quotedText,\n        $dynamicKey: \"dynamic value\"\n      }\n    \"\"\"\n\n    val cursor: HCursor = document.hcursor\n    assertThat(cursor.get[String](\"payload\")).isEqualTo(Right(payload))\n    assertThat(cursor.downField(\"payload\").focus.exists(_.isString)).isTrue\n    assertThat(cursor.get[String](\"quotedText\")).isEqualTo(Right(quotedText))\n    assertThat(cursor.get[String](dynamicKey)).isEqualTo(Right(\"dynamic value\"))\n    assertThat(document.asObject.map(_.keys.toSet.contains(dynamicKey))).isEqualTo(Some(true))\n  }\n\n  @Test\n  def interpolatesJsonFragmentsWithoutStringQuotingThem(): Unit = {"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": 